Tradescantia spathacea Sw. (= Rhoeo discolor (
<normalizedToken originalValue="L’Hér">L'Her</normalizedToken>
.) Hance)
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="51" pageNumber="52" type="names">
<paragraph pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Names.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Myanmar</emphasis>
: 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">mi-gwin-gamone</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">English</emphasis>
: boat lily, Moses in a cradle, oyster plant.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="51" pageNumber="52" type="range">
<paragraph pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Range.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Southern Mexico, Belize, Guatemala and West Indies. Grows throughout Myanmar; cultivated.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="51" pageNumber="52" type="uses">
<paragraph pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Uses.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Whole plant</emphasis>
: One teaspoon of the liquid obtained from pounding the plant mixed with a little sugar (taken three times a day) used to cure coughs and loosen mucus. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Stem</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Leaf</emphasis>
: Liquid obtained from boiling crushed stems and leaves down to 1/3, together with a little raw sugar (1 tablespoon taken three times a day), used to treat vomiting of blood. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Leaf</emphasis>
: Used to remedy burns, scalds, and dysentery.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="51" pageNumber="52" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
In China the plant is used as a poultice on swellings and wounds; the flower is used to treat dysentery, enterorrhagia, and hemoptysis (
<bibRefCitation author="Duke, JA" journalOrPublisher="Lipid / Fett" pageId="172" pageNumber="173" refId="B34" refString="Duke, JA, Ayensu, ES, 1985. Medicinal Plants of China. 2 Vols. Reference Publications, Inc., Algonac." title="Medicinal Plants of China. 2 Vols. Reference Publications, Inc., Algonac." year="1985">Duke and Ayensu 1985</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
